\[
\mathbf{A}^{-1} = \frac{1}{|\mathbf{A}|} \operatorname{bmatrix}
\mathbf{a_2} & \mathbf{a_1}
\end{bmatrix}
\]
The determinant of $\mathbf{A}$ is:
\begin{split}
\vert \mathbf{A} \vert & = ad - 30
\end{split}
Assuming that matrix $\mathbf{A}^{-1}$ is $k\mathbf{A}$, we then have:
\begin{split}
k \mathbf{A} &= k \begin{pmatrix}2 & 3\newline 5 & d\end{pmatrix} =\\
&= \begin{pmatrix} 2k & 3k \newline 5k & dk \end{pmatrix} \\
\mathbf{A}^{-1} &= \frac{1}{ak - 30} \begin{pmatrix}d & -3\newline -5 & 2\end{pmatrix}
\end{split}
This implies that:
